Max Degree of Parallelism (MAXDOP) in SQL Server

Content Owner: Lekireddy Ravinderreddy

"MAXDOP controls how many CPUs SQL Server can use for a single query.
 If it's set too high, big queries may consume all CPUs, causing CPU pressure.
 If too low, complex queries may run slow.
 I usually check the instance MAXDOP setting using sp_configure and adjust based on workload.
 For OLTP systems, I prefer keeping MAXDOP around 2 or 4 to balance CPU usage."

MAXDOP stands for Maximum Degree of Parallelism.
It controls how many CPU cores SQL Server can use to run a single query in parallel.

Simple Example:
If a server has 8 CPUs,
 and MAXDOP = 0,
 SQL Server can use all 8 cores for one large query.

If MAXDOP = 1,
 SQL Server will run the query on just one core (no parallelism).
 MAXDOP settings – 

1.    MAXDOP too high - large queries may consume all CPUs → Causes CPU bottlenecks for other users
2.    MAXDOP too low - Complex queries may run slowly as they can't use multiple cores
3.    Balanced MAXDOP - Better performance without overloading CPU

Default MAXDOP Value:

Default value = 0 - Means: SQL Server decides how many cores to use, based on query cost and server CPUs)

Best Practice Settings (Common Interview Point): Recommended MAXDOP
1.    OLTP (Transactional) - MAXDOP = 4 or MAXDOP = 2
2.    OLAP / Data Warehouse - Can allow higher MAXDOP

Instance Level Setting - sp_configure 'max degree of parallelism'

Check MAXDOP: EXEC sp_configure 'max degree of parallelism';
For individual queries:
 Query can override MAXDOP using query hint: OPTION (MAXDOP 1)

Also, set Cost Threshold for Parallelism to avoid parallel plans for small queries.
